<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-926  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 926.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 29 1990 v24 n5 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Morris verdict stirs debate. (Internet virus case)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The conviction of Robert T. Morris in the Internet virus case isexpected to send a message to computer pranksters, but may notdeter criminal hackers.andP;  Morris was found guilty of illegallyrunning a worm program that disrupted thousands of computers andprevented their use from several hours to several days.andP;  Thelength of Morris' sentence is expected to have an impact on themessage sent to computer hackers.andP;  Legal experts agree that theconviction proves that the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 isadequate for the protection of the nation's computers againstattack and tampering.andP;  The verdict also indicates a change in thenation's views on computer crimes; the hackers are felons, notfolklore heroes.andP;  Morris is due for sentencing in the spring.andP;  Hisconviction will probably not affect his pursuit of a career in thecomputer industry, or even with the federal government, as hiscrime was not fraudulent.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Internet (Computer network)Computer VirusesComputer Crimes.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>